    <fr:title text="Application of rule induction">Application of rule induction</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We recall the <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ={\mathopen {}\left \{a,b\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="jms-016W.xml" title="Syntactic presentation of a formal language" addr="jms-016W" type="local">presented</fr:link> in <fr:link href="jms-016Y.xml" title="A syntactic presentation of a formal language" addr="jms-016Y" type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-016Y" /></fr:link> by the following <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rule</fr:link> set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle }{\displaystyle \quad \epsilon \quad }


 \quad 
 
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle u}{\displaystyle \quad aub\quad }


 \quad 
 
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle u}{\displaystyle \quad bua\quad }


 \quad 
 
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle u\quad  v}{\displaystyle \quad uv\quad }


]]></fr:tex><fr:p>For any <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  {\mathopen {}\left \{a,b\right \}\mathclose {}}^\star ]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P(u)]]></fr:tex> be the property that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> contains the same number of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> symbols. Then for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in  \Sigma ^\star _{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P(u)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7762</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6103</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6103.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We proceed by <fr:link href="jms-0171.xml" title="Rule induction" addr="jms-0171" type="local">rule induction</fr:link>, letting <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S = {\mathopen {}\left \{u\,\middle \vert \,P(u)\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. In particular, we need only show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closed under</fr:link> each of the <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rules</fr:link>:</fr:p>

 <fr:ol><fr:li>We note that the empty string has the same (zero) number of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> symbols.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>Adding both an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> to a given string in whatever location preserves the relationship between the number of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> symbols.</fr:li>
  <fr:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> each and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> each, then the <fr:link href="jms-016J.xml" title="Concatenation of strings" addr="jms-016J" type="local">concatenation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[uv]]></fr:tex> has <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[m+n]]></fr:tex> copies of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> each.</fr:li></fr:ol>

 <fr:p>Therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\in \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> and thus <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star _{\mathcal {R}}\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
