            <fr:anchor>17715</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-0170</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-0170.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="The rule induction principle">The rule induction principle</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>We have been dancing around the relationship between sets of <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">syntactic rules</fr:link> over a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> the subsets of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> that they carve out by means of <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivations</fr:link>. <fr:em><fr:strong>Rule induction</fr:strong></fr:em> is the principle that allows us to prove that these two perspectives are equivalent.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>8</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:anchor>7761</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">jms-0171</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>jms-0171.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Rule induction">Rule induction</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex> be a set of <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">syntactic rules</fr:link> over a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}\subseteq  X]]></fr:tex> be the subset containing just those <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that there exists a derivation of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em><fr:link href="jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closed under</fr:link></fr:em> each of the <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rules</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex> and it is moreover the <fr:em>smallest</fr:em> such subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. In other words, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}\in  \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> and if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\in \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>. Equivalently, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}} = \bigcap  \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>8</fr:day></fr:date><fr:anchor>7760</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">unstable/6102</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-6102.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>We first check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex>. We first fix a <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rule</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle u_1\quad \ldots \quad  u_n}{\displaystyle \quad v\quad }


 ]]></fr:tex>

 <fr:p>We must show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> satisfies the <fr:link href="jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closure condition described</fr:link> by the rule depicted above. For that, we assume that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_1,\ldots ,u_n]]></fr:tex> lie in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> and we need to verify that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex>. By definition, we therefore have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[
 \scriptstyle \frac {\scriptstyle \vdots }{\scriptstyle u_i}
]]></fr:tex> <fr:em><fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivations</fr:link></fr:em> of each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_i]]></fr:tex> and we need to find a <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivation</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>. We do this by combining the assumed <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivations</fr:link> using the rule as follows to obtain a <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivation</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle 
   
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle \vdots }{\displaystyle \quad u_1\quad }

\quad \ldots \quad  
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle \vdots }{\displaystyle \quad u_n\quad }


  }{\displaystyle \quad v\quad }


 ]]></fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
<fr:p>We have therefore shown that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}\in \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>For the remainder of the proof, we fix any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\in \mathcal {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> to check that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}\subseteq  S]]></fr:tex>. In other words, we must prove:</fr:p><fr:blockquote>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> has a <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivation</fr:link> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:blockquote><fr:p>But the above can be rephrased as follows:</fr:p><fr:blockquote>For all derivations <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> generated by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>, the conclusion of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:blockquote><fr:p>As every derivation has a (maximum) height, we can further rephrase the goal in terms that will be amenable to the use of <fr:em>mathematical induction</fr:em>.</fr:p><fr:blockquote>For all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in  \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, the conclusion of any derivation with height less than or equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:blockquote><fr:p>We now proceed by induction.</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>In the <fr:strong>base case</fr:strong>, we must show that the conclusion of any derivation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d]]></fr:tex> with height less than or equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>. But any derivation has height at least <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1]]></fr:tex>, so this is vacuous.</fr:li>
 <fr:li><fr:p>In the <fr:strong>inductive step</fr:strong>, we suppose that the conclusion of every derivation of height less than or equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>; we must prove that the conclusion of every derivation of height less than or equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n+1]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  <fr:p>To that end, consider a derivation of height less than or equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n+1]]></fr:tex> with conclusion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>, which we might depict below as follows:</fr:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
   
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle 
    \frac {\vdots }{u_1}\quad \ldots \quad \frac {\vdots }{u_n}
   }{\displaystyle \quad v\quad }


  ]]></fr:tex>

  <fr:p>Such a <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">derivation</fr:link> must come from a <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">rule</fr:link> of the following form in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
   
 
 \displaystyle \frac {\displaystyle u_1\quad \ldots \quad  u_n}{\displaystyle \quad v\quad }


  ]]></fr:tex>

  <fr:p>We need to show that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>. Naturally, all the <fr:link href="jms-016X.xml" title="Derivations" addr="jms-016X" type="local">subderivations</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_i]]></fr:tex> depicted above have height less than or equal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>; therefore, our inductive hypothesis ensures that each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_i]]></fr:tex> lies in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>The rule <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[
 \scriptstyle \frac {\scriptstyle u_1\quad \ldots \quad  u_n}{\scriptstyle v}
]]></fr:tex> specifies a <fr:link href="jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closure condition</fr:link>, and because <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S\in  \mathrm {Cl}_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> we know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is closed under it. Recalling the <fr:link href="jms-016U.xml" title="The closure condition denoted by a syntactic rule" addr="jms-016U" type="local">closure condition induced by a rule</fr:link>, we can immediately conclude <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v\in  S]]></fr:tex> from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_1,\ldots ,u_n\in  S]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>By virtue of <fr:link href="jms-0171.xml" title="Rule induction" addr="jms-0171" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-0171" /></fr:link>, we are justified in referring to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_{\mathcal {R}}]]></fr:tex> as the subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> <fr:em><fr:strong>inductively defined</fr:strong></fr:em> by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {R}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
