              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>17719</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016W</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016W.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Syntactic presentation of a formal language">Syntactic presentation of a <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link></fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em><fr:strong>syntactic presentation</fr:strong></fr:em> of a <fr:link href="jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">formal language</fr:link> over an <fr:link href="jms-016H.xml" title="Alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a set of <fr:link href="jms-016S.xml" title="Syntactic rule" addr="jms-016S" type="local">syntactic rules</fr:link> over the set of <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">strings</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>17720</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016S</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016S.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Syntactic rule">Syntactic rule</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The basic form of a rule that describes a subset of a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is as follows:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \frac {
  u_1 \quad  \ldots  \quad  u_n
 }{
  v
 }
]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>The plain English meaning of the rule is: <fr:em>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_1]]></fr:tex> through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u_n]]></fr:tex> are elements of the subset that I am defining, then so is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.</fr:em> In such a rule, the items on top of the horizontal line are called <fr:em><fr:strong>premises</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>antecedents</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>hypotheses</fr:strong></fr:em>, and the item on the bottom of the horizontal line is called the <fr:em><fr:strong>conclusion</fr:strong></fr:em>. When a rule has no premises, it is called an <fr:em><fr:strong>axiom</fr:strong></fr:em>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>17721</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016M</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016M.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Formal language">Formal language</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:em><fr:strong>formal language</fr:strong></fr:em> over an <fr:link href="jms-016H.xml" title="Alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a <fr:em>subset</fr:em> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex>, i.e. a set of <fr:link href="jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">strings</fr:link> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>2</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>17722</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-016I</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-016I.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="String over an alphabet">String over an alphabet</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link href="jms-016H.xml" title="Alphabet" addr="jms-016H" type="local">alphabet</fr:link>. A <fr:em><fr:strong>string of length <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex></fr:strong></fr:em> over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is defined to be an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>-tuple of elements of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex>. We write these without any punctuation between them. For example, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[aaabc]]></fr:tex> is a string over the Latin alphabet; we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\epsilon ]]></fr:tex> for the empty string. The set of all strings (of any length) over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> is written <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex>; for a string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in \Sigma ^\star ]]></fr:tex>, we will write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \lvert u\right \rvert \mathclose {}}\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> for its length.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
